05288nam a22006735i 9781501752902DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020003685  a97815017529027 a10.1515/97815017529022doi  a(DE-B1597)546142  a(OCoLC)1139017080  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aDK266.4b.G65 2020 4aDK266.4b.G65 2021 7aHIS0320002bisacsh04a947.0852231 aGolubev, Alexey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Things of Life :bMateriality in Late Soviet Russia /cAlexey Golubev. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2020] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b18 b&w halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction: Elemental Materialism in Soviet Culture and Society -- t1. Techno-Utopian Visions of Soviet Intellectuals after Stalin -- t2. Time in 1:72 Scale: The Plastic Historicity of Soviet Models -- t3. History in Wood: The Search for Historical Authenticity in North Russia -- t4. When Spaces of Transit Fail Their Designers: Social Antagonisms of Soviet Stairwells and Streets -- t5. The Men of Steel: Repairing and Empowering Soviet Bodies with Iron -- t6. Ordinary and Paranormal: The Soviet Television Set -- tConclusions: Soviet Objects and Socialist Modernity -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Things of Life is a social and cultural history of material objects and spaces during the late socialist era. It traces the biographies of Soviet things, examining how the material world of the late Soviet period influenced Soviet people's gender roles, habitual choices, social trajectories, and imaginary aspirations. Instead of seeing political structures and discursive frameworks as the only mechanisms for shaping Soviet citizens, Alexey Golubev explores how Soviet people used objects and spaces to substantiate their individual and collective selves. In doing so, Golubev rediscovers what helped Soviet citizens make sense of their selves and the world around them, ranging from space rockets and model aircraft to heritage buildings, and from home gyms to the hallways and basements of post-Stalinist housing. Through these various materialist fascinations, The Things of Life considers the ways in which many Soviet people subverted the efforts of the Communist regime to transform them into a rationally organized, disciplined, and easily controllable community. Golubev argues that late Soviet materiality had an immense impact on the organization of the Soviet historical and spatial imagination. His approach also makes clear the ways in which the Soviet self was an integral part of the global experience of modernity rather than simply an outcome of Communist propaganda. Through its focus on materiality and personhood, The Things of Life expands our understanding of what made Soviet people and society "Soviet."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMaterial culturezSoviet Union. 0aSpacexSocial aspectszSoviet Union. 4aCultural Studies. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aSoviet material culture, human-object relations, Soviet Social History, Late socialist society, Life in the USSR.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyter